 BANGALORE: India plans to send a manned mission to the moon sometime between 2005 and 2015, a senior space research official said on Saturday.<br>
<br>
&quot;In a few months from now, there will be a review of our plans for a lunar mission. We would first send an unmanned flight around the moon,&quot; said Krishnaswamy Kasturirangan, head of the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO).<br>
<br>
Kasturirangan made the announcement in a speech to the Indian Science Congress. He did not give further details.<br>
<br>
Kasturirangan said India's latest launch vehicle can put satellites weighing up to 2,000 kg into a geostationary orbit, in which a satellite remains above the same spot on earth.<br>
<br>
Future developments will enable the launch of satellites weighing up to 4,000 kg, he told the conference of scientists in Bangalore, India's technology hub.<br>
<br>
