This booster could indeed be scaled up without a whole lot of trouble.  With the exception of the &quot;0 stage&quot; strap-ons, all stages have only one engine each. They could therefore be multiplied to two, three or even four engines per stage without any great engineering problems. <br>
Oddly, the first stage core is solid while the strap-on boosters are liquid, a reversal of the usual pattern seen in such vehicles as Delta. <br>
As it is, low-orbital payload is on the order of 5000 kg. The imminent upgrade to 8000 kg LEO capacity brings manned flight within reach with the easily available Soyuz capsule. Actually, the existing rocket could launch something like Gemini into orbit. I don't know how small a NERVA could be made, but it should certainly be possible to fit one into an 8000kg load, along with a useful amount of propellant, and have this rendezvous with a suitably modified Soyuz. A third launch and second rendezvous could bring up more propellant. At NERVA isp, this would make a direct ascent landing possible with just 3 launches----of a rocket the Indians <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>already have</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Given  the development lead times for very large chemical boosters, this is almost the only way the Indians could make a moon landing by 2005, a very early date specifically mentioned in their announcement. <br>
